tyle="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> not ahead of them</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cyclists can also contribute to improving safety levels and should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">further helped and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">encouraged to do so</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Growth in cycling is a good thing but should not be achieved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">irrespective of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> burden </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">placed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on the rest of society</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HGVs are vital to the functioning of our cities – no other mechanism can deliver the scale of goods we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">require</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> each day without substantially increas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> costs, pollution and congestion</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ncreasing the costs of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">urban </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">freight inc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reases the cost of living in a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ny</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> city</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Any HGV ban is unfeasible, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would increase the cost of living in our cities whilst decreasing economic activity,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">highly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">questionable safety benefit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> FTA strongly opposes any such suggestion</span></li></ul></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Background</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> FTA</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Freight Transport Association is one of Britain’s largest trade associations, and uniquely provides a voice for the whole of the UK’s logistics sector.  Its role, on behalf of over 14,000 members, is to enhance the safety, efficiency and sustainability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of freight movement across the supply chain, regardless of transport mode. FTA members operate over 200,000 goods vehicles - almost half the UK fleet - and some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">one million</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> liveried vans. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Logistics and Road Safety</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ur roads are getting safer, and have b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">een for many years. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Total casualty numbers are reducing. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Much of the impetus for this improvement comes from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the freight industry which has over the years progressively improved the training of drivers, the safety features of vehicles and operating practices – frequently in advance of legal requirements.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Amongst the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">considerable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">general improv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, there is o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ne area that is not getting better:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">yclist </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">casualties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e must understand why, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> other areas of road safety</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">including pedestrian safety</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> continue to improve, cycling is such an exception.  The most obvious change is the increase in cycling on o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ur roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  We do not believe any increase in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cycling cas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">alties can reasonably be attributed to any change within the logistics industry, as the only changes over this time period have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to make logistics safer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as is clearly demonstrated in the industry’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">record relative to pedestrians, motorists and others</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">his </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">does not deflect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the freight industry’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">responsibility for either the current safety record or for making improvements in the future</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  The reality is that in Britain HGVs make up 4% of traffic on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the roads and are involved in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">round 4% of cycling serious injuries, but around 20% of fatalities – with a much higher figure in London.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These figures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would suggest that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">while </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the number of incidents is not higher tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> might be expected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the consequence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of such incidents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">frequently more serious</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As conditions on the road change (ie an increase in the amount of cycling) the freight industry will have to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">continue to adapt </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to meet the new situation.  We are already attempting to do th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is and want </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Responsible operators, such as our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">members</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are investing substantially to upgrade safety features on lorries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, target</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> appropriate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">training </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> drivers, as well as participating in community schemes to promote awareness of how to act safely aroun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d HGVs.  We welcome the recent increase in enforcement against non-compliant HGV operators.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">But we must all understand the full and complex situation regarding safety on our roads and avoid populist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> simplistic solutions or simply demonising any one group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as totally at fault or to blame.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The picture is just not that simple; and solutions are inevitably complex.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Role of HGVs in urban areas</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Why do we have HGVs in our cities?  Urban areas utterly depend on freight. Businesses and homes, hospitals and schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> all rely on efficient logistics to deliver </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">goods and services they need to operate and live, 24 hours a day, seven days a week.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The freight industry does not create this need – we are serving the needs of the society that exists in our cities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n Lond</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on every day over 360,000 tonnes of goods are moved by lorries</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  That’s 15,000 tonnes picked up or dropped off each hour.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These goods are for shops, restaurants, offices and worksites, and without them our cities would cease to function overnight.  Any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">increase in freight costs increases the cost of living in the city.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The role of road freight is irreplaceable in urban areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> - a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lternative modes such as rail and water are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of some but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">limited </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">use here</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  V</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ery few final destinations are actually on a river</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or by a rail terminal.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The HGV is crucial within road freight.  They are the only vehicle capable of delivering the scale of goods that are required everyday </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by our society on our congested roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  A medium sized HGV can carry the same as 10 vans,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a large</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> one more than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">20. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">any loads cannot be broken down into small enough packages to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be moved in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> vans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or the goods being transported – such as concrete - simply cannot be carried in a van</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The congestion and pollution implications of utilising </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">larger number of smaller vehicles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> obvious.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cost of living </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">increases and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">los</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of service for the businesses and residents of cities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, as well as the potential safety implications of bringing many more vehicles into already congested areas, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">must also be taken into consideration</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All measures to improve road safety should be done to allow us all to share the road safely.  Believing that the roads should only be for one group fundamentally misunderstands the role of the road in our society.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The Way Forward - Actions to Take</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As an overall approach, FTA believes that all measures should be intelligent, targeted and evidence based.  It is only by identifying the detailed specific causes of both incidents and the severity of their consequences t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hat we can devise measures that will have the maximum effect.  It is clear that we all want to improve safety in a way that least disrupts the rest of our cities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Based upon our knowledge of HGVs and their interaction with cyclists, FTA would advocate the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">following actions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from all involved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to improve cyclist road safety:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About HGVs</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Enforcement:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> there are tight safety standards set for HGV drivers and operators and they must comply with them.  We understand that low quality operators </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(for example those with any history of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vehicle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">defects, drivers infringements or other non-compliance) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are implicated in a relatively high </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">number</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cyclist incidents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> involving HGVs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">FTA’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> members seek to achieve the highest safety standards and the A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ssociation assists them in doing this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> through the provision of independent vehicle auditing, driver training and tachograph analysis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Therefore we would support further targeted and intelligent enforcement efforts by the police and VOSA as a means to getti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng non-compliant drivers or vehicles off the road.  Drivers who do not pay due care and attention to the road, for example by using handheld phones</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> texting or any other reason</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should be caught and prosecuted.  FTA also recommends to its members that HGV </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">drivers should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">avoid as far as possible the use of even </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hands-free phones</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to reduce as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">much</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as possible the risks of distraction.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Construction logistics</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: construction vehicles (typically the tipper) are found to be highly represented in cycling fatalities.  Therefore safety standards need to improve in this specific sector.  Many large operators are already performing to new higher standards but we need t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o see this become more widespread throughout construction logistics.  To this end FTA has helped develop and will support a new national construction logistics standard </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be launched in December</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in conjunction with industry and cycling groups</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. We will be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">advocating adoption of this across the sector.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Safety equipment exemptions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: remaining exemptions to safety equipment such as side-guards may no longer be appropriate given the conditions on the road.  FTA supports DfT’s initiative to review the status of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he remaining exemptions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">General logistics standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: the general distribution sector (ie outside of specialist areas such as construction logistics) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">operating in urban environments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is keen to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">utilise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">best practice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">guidance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to improve safety.  To t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">his end FTA is working with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> members to develop a general distribution </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cycle safety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">standard and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an accredited </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Training</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: all HGV drivers are trained to a high degree to be entitled to operate such vehicles.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since 2009, drivers are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">required to complete a mandatory 35 hours of additional training over a 5 year period – the Driver Certificate of Professional Competence (DCPC).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We recommend to our members that drivers who operate HGVs in urban areas should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">incorporate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> specific training </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on safe urban driving / vulnerable road users</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as part of this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  The Association however would not want to see this made a compulsory </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">element</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CPC as we believe each driver needs to have a set of courses tailored to their specific needs.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A requirement f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">incorporating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">such training </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is built into the proposed construction standard </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(see para 13) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and should be part of any distribution standard as well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (para 15)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  This would be the best mechanism to ensuring that effective training can be designed and targe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ted at appropriate drivers. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Off peak deliveries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: more can be done to get some HGV movements shifted out of the peak periods when most cyclists are on the road. Especially in London we are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">usually</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> prevented from doing so by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">regulations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  A combination of the London Lorry Control Scheme (LLCS, operated by London Councils), planning conditions and environmental health restrictions prevent movements and deliveries during the night time.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Rather than looking at lorry bans at certain busy pe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">riods, first HGVs should be allowed to operate outside these periods; as is currently not always the case</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  FTA is now involved in a further pilot project with Transport for London and several London Boroughs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on this issue </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and we ask for central and local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">government to support all such efforts.  Whilst for operational and social reasons this will never be a solution for all movements, it is a potentially useful practice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to reduced the need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> HGV movements in peak hours</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Future design of HGVs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: a major lon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g term </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">opportunity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to improve safety would be to improve the design of HGVs.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Much has been done by operators </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in recent years </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to reduce blind spots as far as possible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  However o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ur members currently have to fit additional safety devices on even brand new t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rucks.  There are major gains potentially available form redesigning cabs to increase visibility and ‘rounding’ of the profile of trucks.  We urge the Government to promote the necessary reforms at EU level to allow these developments, and for manufacturer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s to develop new models of HGV design for our members to purchase.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About Infrastructure</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Cycling Infrastructure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: facilities that separate cyclists from motor traffic are highly beneficial and should be developed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wherever</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">possible without unduly disrupting general traffic flow.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Physical access to the kerbside needs to also be preserved for deliveries to be made in order for businesses on the routes to be able to function.  C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ycle lanes that are of high quality in one part a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd low quality or non-existent in other may risk drawing users on to the route that are not confident or capable on certain part of it.  FTA believes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">routes should not be promoted as optimal for cycling until analysis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> suggests the whole route for the typic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al journeys envisaged </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(eg from suburb to city centre) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is ready.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Road layout</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: more can be done to redesign junctions and road layouts to make them safer for all users.  Local authorities, with the support of central Government, should accelerate this redesi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gn process – bearing in mind also the need to maintain effective traffic flow.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Road quality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: there is also a need for all road surfaces to be of a high quality.  Pot holes or other road damage can force cyclists to make manoeuvres that drivers are not expe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cting and increase the risk of incidents.  Local authorities should focus more resources on ensuring cycle-intensive roads are kept to the standard that cyclists require.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About Cycl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Cycling culture</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: cyclist behaviour is a factor in some incidents in wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ich the cyclists suffers.  Evidence from the police’s Stats 19 database, as quoted by cyclist groups, is that the cause of 17-25% incidents resulting in adult cyclist deaths and serious injuries are attributed to the behaviour of the cyclist – a much small</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er figure than for drivers, but not an inconsequential amount.  Beyond these section of incidents, and not attempting to attribute wider ‘blame’ to any cyclist, FTA does believe that the number of incidents could be reduced if slower, more defensive cyclin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g practices are used in our cities – more in line with what </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is recognised as standard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Holland </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Denmark.  This is not to abdicate any of the responsibility where driver actions are the primary cause, but unless we utilise all remedial measures we will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not reduce cycling injuries and deaths as much as we all want.  It should be noted that improved infrastructure may help bring this shift about.  In the meantime we urge government and cycling groups to encourage the emergence of such a culture.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Compliance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: some cyclists do not follow the law or Highway Code when cycling on our streets.  As part of maximising safety as cycling grows, there should be increased enforcement against such infringements and appropriate education or punishment to prevent re-offend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing. Cyclists who break the rules not only endanger themselves but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">put others – especially pedestrians – at risk and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contribute to an unhealthy negative attitude on the roads.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On this basis we welcome the recent increased enforcement efforts by the police in London.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These messages and recommendations apply to drivers as well (see above) – where the scale of punishment will be understandably higher given the nature of the vehicl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e being used.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Training</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: For all users the road is not an intrinsically 100% safe environment.  As we recommend specific training for HGV drivers that operate in urban areas, we believe all cyclists who plan to ride in urban environments should undertake tr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aining.  We want to see government (central and local) do more to provide this training and to encourage urban cyclists to make use of it.  Cyclists need to be helped to be more aware of how to behave safely around HGVs.  The logistics industry needs to co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ntinue and expand its efforts through the Exchanging Places scheme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(public events where cyclists get to sit in the cab of trucks to understand what can and cannot be seen) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and school out-reach programmes to aid this.  FTA also wants to see all cycling trai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ning provided to include HGV awareness.  Government and local authorities should increase their support to ensure this is available and all urban cyclists should be encouraged to take up such opportunities. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Safe practices and safety equipment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: cyclists sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould not distract their attention f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">om the road by listen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to music whilst riding in urban areas.  They should also take up the full range of possible safety equipment – including high visibility markings and helmets.  Again this is not to suggest that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he absence of these is a cause for blame, we merely believe all preventative measures should be taken to reduce the number of incidents or the severity of the consequences as much as possible.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Other</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Information</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: FTA believes more can be done to provide fe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">edback on the detail of incidents – both fatalities and serious injuries.  The more</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> information we have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and the more quickly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it is available</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the better </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we know about what exactly has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contributed to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> incidents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  This would</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enable FTA to provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">members with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">real</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-world examples </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">events and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">avoidance measures that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">en</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> taken – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reinforcing safety messages.  E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">qually this would be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">useful</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for cyclist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Such information would also facilitate more informed public policy debate.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Policies that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">be avoided</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">FTA believes that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">policies that are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">attractive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or tough</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sounding but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not based in evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">massively disruptive to society, should be avoided. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The growth of cycling is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">part of a wider policy designed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to make the country a better place to live </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and to improve peoples’ health </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– it should not be pursued at the expense of making our cities a more difficult place in which to live or work. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are two measures that have been suggested that we would speci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fically wish to oppose on these grounds.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">HGV Bans</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">FTA opposes any suggestion of HGV bans.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The scale of goods needed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the nature of our transport system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> means there is no other way </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n the HGV </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to provide the goods </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our cities need to function</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consequences of a ban would be a mixture of:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Reduced economic activity as costs rise and service is reduced</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Increases in the cost of living in the city</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Congestion and pollution increased through use of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a greater number of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">smaller vehicles</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HGVs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bunching up</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fit in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> during permitted hours – increasing safety risks at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">other times.</span></li></ul><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Those who advocate HGV bans fundamentally misunderstand how integral </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HGVs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the way our society functions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Shops, restaurants, industrial sites</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or other business premi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> do not carry large amounts of stock on site due to the cost of real estate – the entire modern urban business model is based on frequent deliveries as needed.  This is made possible by the HGV as it can be done on a manageable operational and cost basi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s.  Deliveries are also time sensitive.  They are needed at the right time for the service provided (eg shops need goods delivered so that they are ready to serve customers during working hours) and when is compatible with how that business operates (ie sm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all businesses need deliveries to be made when the owner is present).</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To counter this argument, proponents of a ban would say that it is done elsewhere – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">often citing Paris or Dublin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  However</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, this is something of a misconception -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> neither city actually h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as an HGV ban.  In Paris vehicles of at least 28 tonnes, if not higher, can operate anywhere in the city at any time (an HGV is anything over 3.5 tonnes).  More significantly there is a long list of exceptions to the restriction, which includes constructio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n traffic – precisely the traffic that is most notable in incidents with cyclists in London.    </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Dublin regulation is even less of a lorry ban – any size</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> HGV can deliver o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> collect anywhere at any time </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">if they pay </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a €10 charge.  The reason for the reg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ulation is to prevent through traffic from the Port of Dublin </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to the rest of Ireland </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– not a problem London faces as no-one would use central London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a time-saving route</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Aside from the massive economic and social consequences of a ban there are practica</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l questions that appear insurmountable.  </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">When would it apply? – many incidents happen outside any narrow rush-hour window</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (the London Mayor Cycling Commissioner Andrew Gilligan has said that a rush hour HGV ban would only have impacted two of the 14 cycli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng deaths in London this year</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Where would it apply? – many incidents happen outside city centres or off the strategic routes – for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> would all roads in Greater London be covered, in which case the economic consequences would be massive, if it is just the central London area how many incidents would that effect if they are happening elsewhere?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">What would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the safety implications of ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ssively increased numbers of vans on the roads or increased concentrations of HGVs at other times? – we have to consider pedestrians and motor cyclists </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(where total casualty number</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are higher) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as well as cyclists.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">What would happen to HGVs still in the de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">signated area during the relevant period, or outside waiting for it to finish – where would they stop? </span></li></ul><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some proponents of this measure restrict their call to ban “larger” HGVs.  We are unclear what the evidence base is for suggesting that size of HGVs is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">main </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">determining factor in incidents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">frequency or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consequences</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to what extent are 44 tonne articulated lorries delivering to supermarkets the problem? The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">goods </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vehicle most heavily represented in current cycling incidents is the ‘tippe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r’ – which is not defined by size but by function. Tipper HGVs can be just 18 tonnes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  However any size restriction is defined</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> this would still have significant economic, congestion and pollution implications.  But above all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the call for a lor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ry ban </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">does not appear to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">thought-out, sensible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, targeted measure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with demonstrable benefits </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on a safety level.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Strict liability</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a suggestion that in terms of civil liability, the larger vehicle in any collision should be made automatically responsible for any collision.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To our knowledge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> advocates of the proposal have not been able to provide any evidence (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">relying instea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> assumptions) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that this increases safety, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and until th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is is the case, we do not believe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it is worthy of further consideration.  Apportion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing liability upon the basis of balance of probability as to the cause</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, as is currently the case, seems appropriate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We need further action to improve the safety situation on our roads.  The logistics industry needs to change as part of this.  But all actions must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> carefully thought out and tested for what their total imp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">acts and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effect on society </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would be.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">here is a desire to increase cycling because it would be a benefit to society.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This positive outcome</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be achieved by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">imposing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">disproportionate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">costs on that same society.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">6</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">London Freight Data Report: 2012 Update</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">The Guardian, 20 November 2013</span></p></body></html>